<userid>101261121931120971274< /userid><name>Linda Geddis< /name>< date>
1367374114723</date>
<Rate>5</Rate>< text>
This is the best saltwater store I have found in the Riverside area. When you enter the store, it is obvious that the owners know what they are doing - it is well stocked with healthy fish, gorgeous corals and beautiful anemones, and the aquariums are in pristine showcase condition. I will be thrilled if I can get my aquarium to look half as good!

The owner is extremely knowledgeable and won't encourage you to buy something that you don't need, and will help you to find solutions to fit your budget. I brought in a water sample and he tested it for me and discovered that my salinity was too high (despite my hydrometer saying it was okay). My Instant Ocean Hydrometer (which I purchased at a different store) was very inaccurate. He helped me by calibrating my hydrometer allowing me to continue to use it, saving me some money from having to replace it. This is just a small sample of the wonderful service that I have received at Treasures of the Sea and More.

You can trust that you will find expert advice, top quality products and healthy livestock at this store. It is clear that this store is run by people who have a passion for saltwater/reef systems.</text>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
We recommend that store to all citizens of Riverside city and county. The owner was gracious enough to educate us, explain the process of having a salt water fish tank, and how to take care of the fish. What the owner did not know is that I have been a scuba instructor for many years, have had many fish tanks all of my life, graduated with a BS in Biology, and never once, attempted to take advantage of me, or my wallet.

The owner has gained my business, and my trust. Something very difficult to earn this days.

I have had 1 60gallon salt water fish tank for the last 10 years.  I know what I am doing, so does the owner.

Congratulation to Treasures of the sea!!!!!</Review>

< Name>
Tan N Green< /Name>
<time>1373131770547< /time><Rate>4</Rate>< text>
I agree that they are more expensive than other fish stores; however, you have to take into consideration that they have to drive far to get their livestock and then turn around and re-sell them.  Also, they have some of the nicest corals and fish I've seen in the Riverside area.  I purchase my livestock here, simply because I want to see what I'm paying for, versus purchasing on the internet.

And they do give discounts.  Ask the owner for a punch card.  He will give you a discount on your next purchase.

Go there when it's not busy and the owner will make time for you.  Otherwise, get in line...like everything else in life.< /text>

<Response>None<//Response>< Text>
October 1, 2017
Gala occasion uprighting and setting the 60,000 lb Lady Buddha statue at the Bat Nha Temple, 4717 E 1st Street, Santa Ana. The lift was done safely and efficiently by DeWolfe Crane Service. The only problem was that DeWolfe Crane Service was defrauded out of $3608.30 by Holly Pham and Sam Uong- Chi Tha Chua Bat Nha.
We discounted our invoice to help reduce the cost to the Temple and I volunteered to work myself for free, they would only pay the wages of our employees, nothing for the rental of all the equipment.
Holly and Sam conspired with TL Construction/VN Steel to create a situation where it would be very difficult for DeWolfe Crane Service to collect from the Temple because we were working for TL Construction who was under contract from the temple. Holly Pham said the Temple had no money and that she had to give them $1000.00 in order for them to pay the wages of our employees ( I believe she lied about that) and Sam Uong said that we would have to take the Temple to court if I wanted to be paid for the work we did. I believe that the Buddhist people are fair people but for the rest of my life, whenever I see a Buddha statue or temple, I will be reminded of the people that betrayed my trust and defrauded me and my family.
Sincerely, James DeWolfe< /Text>

<UserId.>109010661642495036686<//UserId.><name>Gary Lee Hull</name><Date>1533004743579<//Date>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<Review>The VSO at this historical place, helped me with getting my service connection. He understood perfectly my case, being experienced in all military matters that pertain to helping other Veterans, getting the benefits that they are entitled to receive. Thank You to my VSO officer fellow Veteran George Dixon. I never would have done it without you. He is the best in all he does. He is helping me now to get my upgrade to 100% service connection. I almost gave up on my claim because of the stress, triggering my PTSD making me remember the physical beatings that I went through. I didn't like reliving my tragedies, and, I have been through denials before. I said to myself, This was my last try for my claim, and, if I get denied this time, that's it!!!!; I will NEVER try again for my benefits. But, what happened was that someone told me to go to the Bob Hope Patriotic Hall and go see George Dixon. I did just that and he helped me get 40% service connected the first time out. Now we are working on my 100%  service connection for PTSD, TBI, Military Trauma, Spinal injuries, and other issues that I still suffer from my Military Service. I almost gave up, and, I am glad I didn't give up. They helped me get connected, and, they can help you too. Thanks for your Time, Help, Love, and, support. Respectfully, Gary Lee Hull Disabled Veteran and Musician.
I rate them at a 4 1/2- 5 Star Rating

<Pictures>None<//Pictures>< response>

<gmap_id>0x80c2c7c3e23dca2d:0x95068de3902366e7</gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
< Rating>
1< /Rating>
<Time>1504184653481< /Time>< Text>
This place for veterans? It's a joke. Just like other places supposed to be helping, has one or two good people - see Mr. Dixon and Ms. Stone, a couple (like in two) of helpful and respectful staff, and the rest - just Unpatriotic, Disrespectful mooches that are, pure and simple, ANTI-veterans.
It starts at the door, where security strips you of just about anything they feel like and recommends you "hide" it outside under a trash can!!!
It continues with short Fridays when their schedule is 0800 to 1200. Again, credit needs to be given to Mr. Dixon, who at least on one occasion asked his team on the 2nd floor to stay longer hours, until every veteran that came to their door had a chance to have their question answered.
Also, lots of good things can be said about Ms. Stone and her receptionist who seem to work around the clock, with dignity and care for every veteran.
Then there is the U.S. Vets on the 4th floor, whose representative is as snappy as they come, not helpful as they come, and does little all day besides parading herself in high heels and, yes, even harassing some of the vets. What a useless employee she is!!! When asked about a U.S. Vets event, she referred this vet to the Internet. "Google it", she said, despite the fact that she has a cubicle with a computer and phone at her disposal to HELP the veterans.
Another thing: the building has employee kitchens on every floor, but "according to the rules" not ONE of these kitchens are for veteran use.
Bottled water is available on the 6th floor, by request only. So much for preserving the dignity of the veteran!
On the 6th floor lays the "valor" program. I say lays because it doesn't seem to do anything. The program is currently closed, but I'm not surprised. Other than snutty counselors/social workers giving veterans more pain than gain, there wasn't much about it.
Now the program refers vets out to clinics that serve the general public, and are not dedicated solely to helping veterans.
The 8th floor seems to be for building maintenance people only. Maintenance that is actually so lazy that, hand in hand with security try to actively discourage any homeless veteran that comes through their doors.
Yes, after years and years of coming to the building I accidentally found out that they have showers for the use of homeless veterans, brand new showers built with absolutely no drainage so that upon use, veterans are handed a squeegee and requested that - after the shower - they clean the water that does not drain because of the faulty design. Locks are FORBIDDEN by security from being brought into the building, so there is no way of securing your belongings whle taking the shower: either you take the risk of having your stuff at the mercy of whomever is using the bathroom at the time, or you can safely accommodate only one veteran at the time, which is inefficient.
By the way, shower days are only Monday, Wednesday and Friday, 0800 to 1200. 15 or 20 minutes is all that is allowed for the shower from the moment you get in until you come out.
They also have a couple of other programs, that look more like ghosts, in that I hardly ever heard of them having any events and/ or results, which makes me wonder why they are so vaguely publicized, how come the people working these programs don't seem concerned with their lack of events or results and, oh, yes, HOW do they get their funding with such an insignificant presence?
All in all, Bob Hope Patriotic Hall is a very sad excuse for a veteran resource. With all its majestic appearance - the architecture is just gorgeous - it serves veterans very little - and is a great disappointment, despite a few good men and women that seem to fight a losing battle there in their continued efforts to help the vets. These people I give 5 stars with all my heart, but that is not enough to save the building from being mostly an extravagant continued unjustified spending for the use of the employees and NOT the veterans.< /Text>

Sometimes you just have a craving for a snack in between lunch and dinner.  You don't want it to be too heavy.  In times like these, a spam musubi from L and L hits the spot!  Warm rice with nice hot spray on top.  Put a little bit of sricha sauce, you have a winner.  L and L is a no frills place that makes generous portions of food from the Hawaiian islands.  Good BBQ items.  Staff is wearing masks and there is a bottle of hand sanitizer laying around.< /review>

The inside is dark and reminds me of an English pub, but the outside has a great covered eating/drinking area with air hocky tables.  There is a fabulous patio with views of the Russian River. < review>
Absolutely stunning setting. This had the potential to be a great experience but it was spoiled by the insolent Australian member of staff.

On arrival, we walked through the pub to reach the beer garden, with our dog (a service animal). With no greeting or any respect he marched up and shouted at us for bringing an animal into a bar and told us we should've gone through the side entrance. We stopped in our tracks, speechless. He then ordered us to continue through because we've already come this far.

The beer garden has such a stunning view over the river that we decided to ignore this man. My wife joined the queue for the bar where there's a sign up that says couples have to use the stools and not take up space at the tables, so I chose a pair of stools overlooking the river.

When my wife came back with the drinks she said she'd rather sit in the shade, if possible. Despite there being plenty of shaded seating around the large (mostly empty) tables, I didn't want to get shouted at again so decided to shift the pair of stools a few feet to the right, so they're in the shade. The Ozzy t**t must've been watching our every move because before I even lifted the first stool he aggressively shouted, "DON'T MOVE THE FURNITURE!". Seriously?

I calmly approached him and asked what the solution should be, since we want to sit in the shade but the sign says we have to sit on stools. He unapologetically directed us to sit at the tables and ignore the sign. Wait, so now it's ok to ignore signs?

By this point we just wanted to drink our drinks and get the hell out of there before I lost my temper with this a-hole. Having read some of the other one-star reviews I can see that other people had a similar experience with him.

We would definitely go back, if he wasn't working there.</review>

< Review>
This is a place made to just hang out and chill. The house beers are great. The garlic fries are really garlicky. The patio has an air hockey table, and a pool table. The stairs down to the beach on the Russian River are for the customers. There is no waitstaff, per se, you go to the bar to order and pay for drinks, then you go to the grill and order food and pay there. They give you a buzzer to let you know when it's ready to pick up. Note: this is a cash-only operation! No credit cards. But it is a place where people come to just hang and relax.<//Review>

<Rate>1</Rate>< Review>
First (& 2nd impressions) of a place are hard to get past when they aren't good but I will try to give Stumptown another chance.

It would be nice to drink the beer here but the last two times I've attemted to do so the bartender has not greeted me, ignored me to the point where I had to be the one to get her attention, and seemigly just plain unenthusiastic about the beers Stumptown serves.  When I told her that it was my first time she pointed to the chalkboard as if the names of their beers mean anything to me and when she came back around to take my order I told her I don't know what to order. There aren't many micro brews I don't like but there were a couple IPAs on tap so I told her I like IPAs in hopes she would give me more information and I could make the best choice. She said the Haze IPA is good (no tasting notes, no what differentiates it from the other IPAs, no sample, etc...just "good") but since she made an actual suggestion & I hope to eventually taste all the beers here anyways that is what I went for.  Ultimately I didn't end up ordering because it was cash only and I didn't have enough for food+beer+tip & on top of those costs paying an ATM fee wasn't worth it in return for the cruddy service I was receiving.  I couldn't figure out maybe if I just visited when this bartender is having a bad day, if it's just me she treats that way (this was the 2nd time I went in and she wasn't very welcoming then either), or if she doesn't like/ isn't knowledgeable enough about the beer she is serving which is why she can't talk about it, or if perhaps she is  just really bad at customer service.

Whatever the case I plan to come back in the future,  with cash ofcourse, but when this gal bartender isn't the one serving me. Hard to go to a place that doesn't seem all in on their product or accustomed to bare minimum welcoming a person who is wanting to be there. So hopefully I will have better experience next time and I I can make this a regular spot.< /Review>

<rate>1<//rate><UserId.>103355876071504852667</UserId.><Text>After spending a full day floating on the river, it would be nice to grab a pint and a burger on the deck along the river, but you won't find that here.  The kitchen is cash only and closes at 4p, right when you come off the river hungry and thirsty.  The employees had an attitude when we came in at 3:45 and they exclaimed it would be "a dick move to order food so close to closing".  If the kitchen is open till 4, they should serve food till 4.  This was a reluctant second chance after the first time I went here two years ago with a large group of friends.  We all ordered food and a beer and as I watched all my other friends get their food and eat, my order never came. <user_id>114596361411457591114<//user_id><name>Russian River Vacation Homes< /name><pictures>None< /pictures>< Review>
Stumptown Brewery is as local as it gets for local beer. And not many breweries have a separate yard where your dog can hangout while you have a beverage... Or a place to pull up from the river and eat lunch and keep paddling - or dinner when you're done for the day - a cold beer is awfully good sounding when you are headed down the river. Stumptown has all of the above.

The food is bar food and cash only. Burgers, fries, onion rings, and such.

The back deck is extensive and awesome for hanging out and looking at the river... And the lower lawn is home to the annual Beer Revival and BBQ cook off.<//Review>

<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>As far as Japanese grocery stores go, we in the Los Angeles area are pretty fortunate. We have Nijiya, Mitsuwa, and others though few are as big as this branch of Tokyo Central. You can find not only the standard fare of snacks, groceries, and Japanese food staples but there are also restaurants as well as a whole floor of home goods, tshirts and so on. Definitely worth a stop if you are in the area.< /Text>< Pics>

< Review>
The best experience ever among all the Tokyo central. I think this is the largest store here in Los Angeles areas. Foods are diverse and fresh, a lot of sashimi choices. The food court is still close due to COVID and it is slightly crowded during the weekend. But again, it is a great store and highly recommended. Even if you don't want to buy anything, walking around here is time well spend< /Review>

< review>
I LOVE this store. They try their best to label everything in English to make it more accessible to folks.

If youre going to buy the plates make sure you show up before 7. At 7 pm they go on sale for 20% off but by then there's little to nothing left. People come in a little before 7 and stack their carts. Come earlier and pay full price if you really want to be able to have options.<//review>

< Text>
Very clean inside.  Due to Covid-19 protocol, limited people were allowed inside the market.  But the line moves very fast.  They have some good fresh vegetables, fruits and meat section.  They have this Passion Orange Guava (POG) in 1 quart carton at the refrigerator section.  They also have one of the best deal in bento boxes meal.  A box costs between 5.99 to 6.99.  Fresh sushi, maki rolls, all at a good price.</Text>

Tokyo Central Market is huge, clean, and well organized. Unfortunately, due to the COVID-19 pandemic era, the upper stores are closed.

<user_name>Sarah (Sarah_of_all_trades)<//user_name>< text>
I love Tokyo Central! There is literally nothing that I can't find. It is a two-story haven of Asian merchandise and food with excellent quality and service.If you're on the first floor you can find items like massagers, face and beauty supplies, food supplies, kitchen supplies, school supplies, and decoration materials. If you go to the second floor you can find everything from Japanese doll robes and clothes to decorations and house decor. all the items are recently priced and the staff is willing to negotiate. It's a wonderful location and I would be surprised if they didn't have what you were looking for.</text>

< review>
I love this place, but I wish they took covid more seriously at this location. For some reason management doesn't seem to care about the health of there customers at this specific location. Baskets aren't wiped down, the number of people in the store isn't monitored and there are plenty of customers allowed to walk around maskless.

We try not to go to this location, if possible, because other Tokyo Centrals in L. A. Do a great job so we drive 30 minutes longer to be safer.

They would normally get 5 stars but Management's disregard of safety is just too big a deal for me and my family.< /review>

<review>My wife, who is Japanese, and I started to go to TCM Redondo Beach Blvd and Artesia Blvd at the beginning of the pandemic. Now we rarely go to the Ralph's in our neighborhood. The meat selection at TCM is 1000 times better than Ralph's for cooking Japanese food because it is sliced properly. Moreover, the fruits and vegetables are the freshest and cheapest. The Mammoth Bakery inside the TCM on RB Blvd is our favorite place to buy sliced bread, perfect for breakfast toast. We can get Crystal Geyser Water for only 79 cents a gallon! We can also get very Japanese vegetable, fruit, and herb we need there. The Artesia Blvd one has great restaurants and a bakery inside. They also have the best selection of meat and bento, IMO. I loved their karaage chicken deli, but they closed it. Their 2nd floor has character goods, cooking appliances, and clothes. My wife occasionally gets stuff up there. I love their various "fairs." We got a lot of stuff during their KAGOSHIMA Fair. It is so cool to be able to get the real taste of Japan here in So Cal.</review>< Pics>

Large and has mostly everything you need. But be warned if you decide to go here. They get really long lines. <review>The BEST in LA!
Seriously Huge and Packed with just about Everything you could want from a Japanese supermarket and goods store. Makeup, detergent, furniture, stationary, gifts, home goods, electronic dictionaries, air conditioners, cookware, kitchen goods, stuffed animals, phone accessories, car scents, etc etc etc. Just Huge and the biggest, most well-stocked shop period among all of the Tokyo Central, Nijiya, Mitsuwa, and other Japanese supermarket centers in Los Angeles.
A handful of restaurants from takoyaki to karage for takeout.
Latest corona remodel gets rid of the antique furniture $$$, closed the dining (can still take out), adds a big stationary section with more pens and pencils than Kinokuniya, even more housewares, beauty supplies, tons of boxed take out meals, etc.
And prices are among the lowest at Japanese markets in L.A.
Seriously, the ONLY Japanese supermarket you need to shop at - a mini Bic Camera or Yodabashi!!< /review><Time>1605836603075<//Time>< Resp>

< Review>
$2.87 for a bag of ORGANiC ginger; as of february 2019.

This market caters to customers that have high standards for quality produce. The mandarin fruits are consistently of high quality. Its not the cheapest market to shop for produce but there are always deals for some of the items. You can save yourself some serious dollars if you keep checking what is on sale and when.

< Review>
Ahhhh my most favorite Tokyo Central in all the land. Rows and rows of Japanese goods, groceries, and hard to find items you'd only get in Japan. Produce was fresh as usual. The home goods store has great everyday supplies - got a (Made in Japan) donabe on sale. The food court has a great takoyaki vendor. I only wish this Tokyo Central had a hot food bar like the one in Costa Mesa!< /Review>

< text>
This used to be marukai but I guess they got bought out by Tokyo central. It's still pretty much the same though except the dining area got upgraded especially the outdoor part. This market has a big Japanese cosmetics, lifestyle, home goods area which I love! I think if I ranked the Japanese market this would be on top closely after nijiya. Mitsuwa is prettier but it doesn't have as many items. Also this market has the best chicken karaage in their food court. Always super crowded ( which is bad during this pandemic) but theres a reason why so many people go here.< /text>

< text>
Love this japanese market, it has everything you need if you are in need of Japanese food and food. Has basic everyday household Japanese appliances, rice cooker, humidifier, hot water maker, dishes, cups, and a bunch of other cute useful Japanese things you want but you don't need. Awesome food selection, lots of reasonably priced fresh vegetables and fruit. Has organics and imports from Japan. Fresh fish from Japan and local, at reasonable prices. The meat selection is amazing the best meat you could probably get anywhere. The snacks and all Japanese ingredients you need they will have it at a good price.

They also have a food court area if you come during the busy hours of the day. The pork buns are amazing. Sometimes it gets busy so pick wisely what time if the day you decided to go. The structure is difficult to get in on Artesia. I use to pass it a few times before i was able to identify it. It's surrounded by a green fence all around.<//text>

< user_name>
Wesley Krueger</user_name>
<rate>4</rate><user>109214225129615227111< /user>< Text>
This place was originally known as Marukai, I'm not sure when they changed the name. Inside you can find a couple small restaurants, groceries, and novelty products.

Downstairs, they have a large selection of meats, vegetables and drinks/beer. Also available are many Japanese snacks and candy (these alone make a trip worth it in my opinion).

Upstairs, their products range from furniture to figurines. They have a lot of novelty and comfort items, including the full size pajamas with a hood known as kigurumi, and blind boxes containing random cute figurines.

This store can make for a fun browsing experience, and can also satisfy a grocery trip. I can only caution that with all of the neat things they have here is that you might spend more money than you plan to.<//Text>

< Review>
I recommend this place especially for anyone that cooks, and is looking for Japanese ingredients.  The perishables here are generally more fresh than what you're likely to find at similar Japanese markets in the area.  You can also find prepared food, kitchen goods, cosmetics, and various knickknacks all in one convenient location.
Note though that the discounted prices throughout the market require a membership card at the cost of $1 (with no recurring fees).< /Review>

<user_name>J & A< /user_name><time>1562889645800<//time><rate>5<//rate><Review>This place has everything you can think of for a Japanese market. It's really a mega store. Deli, fresh sushi counter, a few fast food stands, inside & outside eating areas, grocery store with impressive selections of Japanese goods, very fresh produce, well stocked liquor area (could not find Okinawan saki unfortunately). The downstairs also houses a separate cosmetics section, it is so big it is a little overwhelming & I honestly didn't know what half the stuff was meant for since I'm not able to read the letters. It also has a separate appliances area with rice cookers and small things like that. The upstairs has all the fun stuff. Things like kimonos (some moderate priced used ones) wooden sandals, cute hair clips, Zen gardens, lucky cats, dolls, trinkets, stuffed animals, crazy socks, kigurumi (onesies), costumes, models, Pokemon stuff.
Also, everyone that works here is super helpful if you have questions about anything so don't hesitate to ask.
Overall, you could spend a few hours exploring this place, shopping, having lunch & have a great time doing it.<//Review>< Pictures>

< text>
This place has everything you can think of for a Japanese market. It's really a mega store. Deli, fresh sushi counter, a few fast food stands, inside & outside eating areas, grocery store with impressive selections of Japanese goods, very fresh produce, well stocked liquor area (could not find Okinawan saki unfortunately). The downstairs also houses a separate cosmetics section, it is so big it is a little overwhelming & I honestly didn't know what half the stuff was meant for since I'm not able to read the letters. It also has a separate appliances area with rice cookers and small things like that. The upstairs has all the fun stuff. Things like kimonos (some moderate priced used ones) wooden sandals, cute hair clips, Zen gardens, lucky cats, dolls, trinkets, stuffed animals, crazy socks, kigurumi (onesies), costumes, models, Pokemon stuff.
Also, everyone that works here is super helpful if you have questions about anything so don't hesitate to ask.
Overall, you could spend a few hours exploring this place, shopping, having lunch & have a great time doing it.< /text>

<text>Very clean and friendly. They had everything I needed< /text>< gmapID>

<user>101817716578675297780< /user></record>
</dataset><record>
<UserId.>115366180693589039249<//UserId.><username>John Jiao< /username><Time>1544475653607< /Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
I'm a Hawaii native, so I've been exposed to a lot of American-Japanese food/culture/etc, and this place is easily the BEST Japanese market I've ever been to. If you're into Hawaiian food, there's multiple aisles of stuff I've literally never seen outside of Hawaii before --- authentic portugeuse sausage, lau lau, every single type of sugary drink (POG, passion orange, etc), even frozen Zippys meals (!!!)

From a Japanese standpoint, everything is not only directly imported, but there are little English descriptions of all the foods on the price labels. All the staff are super courteous, and the food court attached is out of this world!

A real shining star here is the sushi --- it's cheaper, fresher, and tastier than you'll be able to get anywhere else that I've ever seen. There's also an authentic Japanese curry stand in the back corner where you can get all kinds of amazing curry dishes. The food court has some of the best karaage chicken I've ever had, and this is the first time I've seen an authentic takoyaki stand in LA.

All in all, amazing service, amazing prices, and a must-go for anybody who loves Japanese food.<//review>

<Time>1532326046954<//Time><Text>This place has it all as far as a Japanese style market goes.

It has all the dry goods to make whats popular at home. All the frozen goods to take home and eat and also a nice little fiod court area to get some pretty decent food.

The Store also has a floral area and a toys/Japanese hobby section even have the paints you need to paint them. Pretty cool!

There lots of cool japanese nicknacks and little gifts if you want to gift some one something cool.

<user>113044265628566895776< /user><Name>Brian Garant<//Name><Date>1423595906574</Date><Rate>5<//Rate><review>One of, if not THE, best Japanese supermarkets in the Los Angeles area. My family has been going here for years and, more often than not, we always find what we need. The prices can skew a little high on some items, I find that I can usually do my produce shopping elsewhere and save a little, but in general the prices are fine. It can get a little cramped inside on weekends and you should absolutely be prepared for a wait in the checkout line. For years I shopped at their satellite store in West Covina (closed now, sadly) and while it was much closer that was about the only thing it had up on the Gardena store. Consistently clean and, aside from one experience with a belligerent employee, the staff is great. I've tried most of their competitors over the years and have consistently come back to Marukai.<//review><pics>None<//pics>< resp>

< review>
This is one of the better Marukais. They have everything that you could want.  The service sucks, though.  It serves the Nisei (2nd gen) crowd vs Mitsuwa or Nijiya which serves more of the Issei (1st gen) or Japanese transplant crowd.
Marukai is generally the cheapest of the 3 Japanese market chains, but I feel that the quality also suffers a bit.  Korean markets are cheapest for pretty much everything, so if you have a good Korean market nearby, I would generally opt to go there over Marukai.</review>

<user_id>110460545332954816496< /user_id><username>Cat Manabat< /username>< date>
1491661457496< /date>
< rating>
4<//rating>
< Review>
I heart Murakai so much. I am much closer to the Little Tokyo location, but what I love about the Gardena Murakai is that it is way bigger and never gets as crowded as the Little Tokyo one. (We all want to avoid that moment when you and an elderly lady are eyeing that last packet of whatever...and you briefly wonder if it's socially acceptable to elbow her out of the way.)

I usually pick up saimin ingredients, my favorite snacks, and other packaged items so I can't speak for any of the hot food or even packaged pastries there...but they always have what I need and then some. Sure, I need a mini stapler and a panda-shaped mug. Sure, I need taro pancake mix and strawberry Kit Kats. Why the eff not? The cashiers are super nice as well.

I did knock off a star because I happened to use the bathroom once and it was...not pretty. Also, the place in general is grungy (probably just old) but well-organized and the aisles are always clean.<//Review>
